2nd exercise: Data summary and regression analysis basics

The exercise consist 5 parts, which are separated in own sections (below). Data for the exercise was read from http://www.helsinki.fi/~kvehkala/JYTmooc/JYTOPKYS3-data.txt and it was processed (data wrangling) using a R script (create_learning2014.R). Data is stored into /data/learning2014.csv file. I won’t go into details about the data wrangling, so look at the file if interested.

Scripts can be found from my /scripts folder in IODS-project’s github repository.

1st part

First things first, so let’s read the data

learning_data <- read.table("data/learning2014.csv",sep=",",header=T)

Data in this exercise is sample of bigger student questionnaire. It has 7 variables and 166 observations and the structure is following:

str(learning_data)
## 'data.frame':    166 obs. of  7 variables:
##  $ gender  : chr  "F" "M" "F" "M" ...
##  $ Age     : int  53 55 49 53 49 38 50 37 37 42 ...
##  $ Attitude: int  37 31 25 35 37 38 35 29 38 21 ...
##  $ deep    : num  3.58 2.92 3.5 3.5 3.67 ...
##  $ stra    : num  3.38 2.75 3.62 3.12 3.62 ...
##  $ surf    : num  2.58 3.17 2.25 2.25 2.83 ...
##  $ Points  : int  25 12 24 10 22 21 21 31 24 26 ...

Questionnaire is about different kind of studying orientations. Orientation approaches were deep, surface (surf) and strategic (stra) approached orientations. In addition, gender, age, points and attitude were recorded from the students.

2nd part

In table (below), is summary of data. One third of students were male. The median age was 22, but having a some old students too.

Summary of the data is shown in figure (below). The figure represents distributions for all variables and correlations between them. Some of the distributions have quite significant tails (for example, age, deep, and attitude). of the distributions have bet and At first glance, it looks like that there is no difference between gender (red: female, green:male). However, it looks like that males reported higher attitude than female, but that is probably quite normal :D (swagger males). Quick analysis reveals that surface and deep approaches correlates, and student’s attitude correlates with the total points after orientation year.
